  "summary": "Hakast and Colin Lamb discuss the ongoing murder investigation at Pema-Chhoe's house. Hakast suspects Hillary Weber, the woman who discovered the body, noting that her lunch break coincides with the estimated time of death. Colin questions this suspicion due to Weber's apparent distress. He notes that Pema-Chhoe is a blind woman who previously worked as a math teacher before being employed at the Allenberg Institute. Hakast reveals that their investigation into a man named Kirby has been fruitless, as his business card, name, address, and the Big City Small Town Insurance Company all appear to be fabrications. An autopsy has determined the victim was killed with a sharp instrument, such as a kitchen knife.\n\nThe investigators consider seeking clues from neighbors in the upper-class residential area of Wilbraham Crescent. Hakast identifies number 18 as the residence of Edith and James Waitehouse, an assistant at a law firm. James expresses concern to his sister regarding recent suspicious activity in the neighborhood, but Edith dismisses his fears. Edith discusses rumors that the victim may have been an accountant from Allerton College investigating financial discrepancies. She defends Pema-Chhoe’s character, rejecting the theory that she strangled the man. After James leaves for work, an agitated Edith places a nine-iron from her golf bag near the front door for protection.",
